# S3 — Simple Storage Service

S3 is object storage. Not a filesystem — you store objects (files) in buckets, access them via HTTP, and they scale infinitely. It is one of AWS's oldest and most reliable services and shows up everywhere: static assets, backups, Terraform state, CI artifacts, logs, ML datasets.

---

## Core Concepts

**Bucket** — A container for objects. Name must be globally unique across all AWS accounts. Tied to a region even though the name is global.

**Object** — A file + metadata. Identified by a key (the "path"), e.g. `uploads/2024/06/image.jpg`. Objects can be up to 5TB.

**Key** — The full path to an object within a bucket. S3 is flat (not a real filesystem), but `/` in key names creates the appearance of folders in the console.

**Storage Classes:**

| Class | Use Case | Retrieval |
|-------|----------|-----------|
| S3 Standard | Frequently accessed data | Immediate |
| S3 Standard-IA | Infrequent access, still fast | Immediate |
| S3 Glacier Instant | Archives, millisecond retrieval | Immediate |
| S3 Glacier Flexible | Archives, cheap | Minutes–hours |
| S3 Intelligent-Tiering | Unknown access pattern | Immediate |

