## Terraform State Backend

S3 is the standard backend for Terraform state. You will configure this in the Terraform module.

```hcl
# backend.tf
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket         = "my-terraform-state-bucket"
    key            = "prod/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "ap-south-1"
    encrypt        = true
    dynamodb_table = "terraform-locks"
  }
}
```

Always enable: versioning (to recover from bad state), encryption, and DynamoDB locking (prevents concurrent applies).

---

## Key Insight for DevOps

S3 is eventually consistent for some operations (though AWS has moved toward strong consistency). For Terraform state, this is why DynamoDB locking matters — without it, two simultaneous `terraform apply` commands can corrupt your state file.

Never store secrets in S3 without encryption. Enable SSE-S3 or SSE-KMS at the bucket level, and for anything sensitive, use SSE-KMS with a dedicated KMS key so you get audit logs of every decryption.